Observation Details: One very unique sparrow with what has been dubbed the "brown mutation" by researcher Hein van Grouw (link: http://archive.sciendo.com/ISSPAR/isspar.2012.36.issue-1/isspar-2015-0012/isspar-2015-0012.pdf). The mutation effects the oxidation of eumelanin, lightening all but the already lighter reddish/brown shades. The feathers are also prone to further bleaching from sunlight over time.  Judging from the samples seen in Grouw's paper, this is likely older plummage given the lighter tones.

Observation Details: A male with relatively early coloration disorder of "progressive graying." Asymmetrical appearance of scattered white feathers (as opposed to symmetrical appearance in leucism). Not "partial albinism" because that does not exist (there is only albinism in which the bird is all white except for pink eyes, bill and feet.) See http://dx.doi.org/10.25226/bboc.v141i3.2021.a5 for further details about melanin abnormalities.

Discovered a male House Sparrow in our yard by the bird feeders, chocolate brown on back of head, gray crown, dark mask in front of eyes extending below chin, very warm, creamy tone on wing feathers. All light, gray chest, belly and center of back between wings, thick black bill. Very common bird in my home country Germany and also in places down south but not here in Juneau. I believe this is only the third recorded House Sparrow for the Juneau area.
